# 41_objects_group_ungroup — closes the `objects` arc's m5
# (collection-level grouping) and the canvas-observable arc.
#
# s242 m1 shipped the GroupNodesCommand / UngroupNodeCommand
# infrastructure (iid-migrated structural commands; first new
# structural commands built in the migrated capture shape) and
# migrated Canvas::group_selection / Canvas::ungroup_selection to
# push them. Both group and ungroup are now properly undoable from
# the canvas side — a pre-existing architectural gap closed in m1.
#
# s242 m2 (this smoke) ships the script-side wrap:
#   - `objects group <iid1> <iid2> ...` — wraps two or more
#     sibling scene objects in a new Group. Returns the Group's
#     iid as text (so callers can `set g to result` and address
#     the group via `objects.g` from then on). Pushes
#     GroupNodesCommand.
#   - `objects ungroup <iid>` — dissolves the named Group,
#     promoting its children to the parent. Returns null. Pushes
#     UngroupNodeCommand.
#
# This is the canvas-observable arc's m5 close. With group +
# ungroup landing, every collection-level structural verb the
# canvas surface has is now also addressable from scripts (new /
# delete / find_by_name / find_by_type / group / ungroup) plus the
# proxy-side mutating and structural verbs from m3 and m4. The
# `objects` Tier 3 entry now books — eleventh "fits unmodified"
# would apply EXCEPT this milestone shipped the commands itself
# rather than reusing existing ones, so the verify-before-assume
# streak takes a different kind of step here: the commands were
# DESIGNED for these verbs, so the "fit" is by construction rather
# than coincidence. Different shape, same outcome.
#
# Material differences from the m3/m4 element verbs:
#   - Collection-level invoke, not proxy-level. group and ungroup
#     live on the `objects` Scriptable directly, same surface as
#     new / delete / find_by_name / find_by_type. The DSL grammar
#     is `objects group <iid> <iid> ...` (no proxy chain), same
#     shape as `objects new "path"`.
#   - Variadic args on group. Earlier verbs took 0 or 1 args; group
#     takes 2..N. The args.size() < 2 guard is the new vocabulary
#     this milestone introduces. ungroup is 1-arg like delete.
#   - Atomic siblings-check on group. Before doing anything, the
#     verb walks every supplied iid and verifies (a) each resolves
#     to an in-scope scene object, (b) each is a direct child (not
#     in a non-children slot like clip_shape), (c) all share the
#     SAME parent. Cross-parent grouping is refused; the verb
#     returns "" and no command is pushed. Same atomic posture
#     GroupNodesCommand uses on execute.
#   - Parent-z-order capture. The order the script lists iids in
#     doesn't determine the group's internal stacking — the verb
#     walks the parent's children once and plucks the matched
#     ones in that order. Same rule Canvas::group_selection
#     enforces. A script that writes `objects group p3 p1 p2`
#     gets a group whose children are in parent-z-order, not
#     [p3, p1, p2].
#   - Both verbs push commands via the s242 m1 iid-migrated
#     structural commands. Ctrl+Z dissolves the group; Ctrl+Y
#     re-wraps with the SAME group iid (so any script-side
#     variable holding the group iid stays consistent across
#     undo/redo cycles).
#
# ── Owns-its-conditions structure (CANON) ────────────────────────────────
#
# BUILD UP / VALIDATE / TEAR DOWN. The smoke mints its own test
# layer and three test Paths, validates the group / ungroup
# surface end-to-end, and tears everything back down. Net
# structural change to the doc: zero. Side effects on the undo
# stack: AddNodeCommand for the mints, EditPathCommand for the
# geometry sets, GroupNodesCommand / UngroupNodeCommand for the
# grouping ops, DeleteObjectCommand for the teardown.
#
# ── Pre-stated count ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Expected: 15 pass / 0 fail / 0 error.
#
# Breakdown:
#   Phase 1 (REGISTRY):                                       → 0 asserts.
#   Phase 2 (DISPATCH — baseline count):                      → 0 asserts.
#   Phase 3 (BUILD UP — mint test_layer, three Paths):
#     p1 type == "path"                                        → 1 assert.
#   Phase 4 (GROUP — wrap p1+p2+p3 into a new Group g):
#     g type == "group",
#     g child_count == 3                                       → 2 asserts.
#   Phase 5 (VERIFY children parented to g):
#     p1 parent_iid == g,
#     p2 parent_iid == g,
#     p3 parent_iid == g                                       → 3 asserts.
#   Phase 6 (UNGROUP — dissolve g, children back to test_layer):
#     p1 parent_iid == test_layer,
#     p2 parent_iid == test_layer,
#     p3 parent_iid == test_layer                              → 3 asserts.
#   Phase 7 (NEGATIVE — group with single arg refused; p1 stays
#            where it was):
#     p1 parent_iid == test_layer                              → 1 assert.
#   Phase 8 (NEGATIVE — ungroup wrong-type refused; p1 is a Path
#            not a Group, command refuses, p1 stays a Path under
#            test_layer):
#     p1 type == "path"                                        → 1 assert.
#   Phase 9 (REGROUP — re-wrap to confirm the verb's repeatable):
#     g2 type == "group",
#     g2 child_count == 3                                      → 2 asserts.
#   Phase 10 (CROSS-CHECK — find_by_type "group" resolves):
#     found_group type == "group"                              → 1 assert.
#   Phase 11 (TEAR DOWN — round-trip count via subtree-delete):
#     objects count == count_before                            → 1 assert.
#
# Total: 0 + 0 + 1 + 2 + 3 + 3 + 1 + 1 + 2 + 1 + 1 = 15.
#
# ── On the parent-z-order rule (Phase 4) ─────────────────────────────────
#
# The smoke mints p1, p2, p3 in that order — `objects new` inserts
# at the front of children (z-top), so after the three mints the
# parent's children are [p3, p2, p1] (p3 is z-top). The script then
# calls `objects group p1 p2 p3` (selection-order). The verb walks
# parent->children once, plucks p3 (idx 0), p2 (idx 1), p1 (idx 2)
# in that order, and the group lands with children [p3, p2, p1].
# Phase 4's `child_count == 3` doesn't expose the order, but
# Phase 5's three parent_iid asserts are order-independent —
# whichever way the children landed in the group, each one's
# parent_iid is g.
#
# ── On the variadic-args grammar (Phase 4) ───────────────────────────────
#
# The DSL parses `objects group p1 p2 p3` as four tokens after
# `objects`: the verb name `group` and three string-shaped args.
# Each arg passes through arg_as_string. Same way `objects new
# "path"` parses with one arg; same way `find_by_type "group"`
# parses with one arg. Variadic >2 is the new shape this verb
# introduces.
#
# ── On the cross-parent refusal (NOT tested here) ────────────────────────
#
# A future expansion of this smoke would mint a second test layer,
# place an object on it, then attempt `objects group <obj_on_layer_1>
# <obj_on_layer_2>` and assert the empty-string return. This
# milestone keeps the smoke focused on the happy path plus the two
# negative cases that don't require multi-layer setup (too-few
# args, wrong-type to ungroup). Cross-parent coverage is logged
# for a future smoke-expansion milestone.
#
# ── Canvas-observable (three-channel acceptance) ─────────────────────────
#
# Trace channel: the 15 asserts above.
# Visual channel: the layers panel SHOULD show the group / ungroup
#   transitions in real time as the smoke runs — three Rectangle
#   rows under "objects_group_ungroup_smoke_s242_m2" briefly,
#   then those three indented one level deeper under a new "Group
#   N" row (Phase 4), then the group dissolves and they un-indent
#   (Phase 6), then they re-indent under "Group N+1" (Phase 9),
#   then everything cleans up (Phase 11). m1's manual canvas test
#   already confirmed the panel does this correctly for group /
#   ungroup; this smoke just exercises the same path from script.
# Build channel: Scott's compile.

#[sub] === Phase 1: REGISTRY ===
#[sub] `objects` should appear in the registry list — baseline.

list

#[sub] === Phase 2: DISPATCH — baseline count ===
#[sub] Captures the pre-mint object count to compare against after
#[sub] teardown.

get objects count
set count_before to result

#[sub] === Phase 3: BUILD UP — mint test layer, three Paths ===
#[sub] Mint a sentinel-named test layer, activate it, mint three
#[sub] Path objects with geometry. They'll be the targets for the
#[sub] grouping ops.

layers new
set test_layer to result
layers.test_layer rename "objects_group_ungroup_smoke_s242_m2"
layers.test_layer activate

objects new "path"
set p1 to result
objects.p1 set_path_data "M 0 0 L 100 0 L 100 100 L 0 100 Z"

objects new "path"
set p2 to result
objects.p2 set_path_data "M 150 0 L 250 0 L 250 100 L 150 100 Z"

objects new "path"
set p3 to result
objects.p3 set_path_data "M 300 0 L 400 0 L 400 100 L 300 100 Z"

assert objects.p1 type == "path"

#[sub] === Phase 4: GROUP — wrap p1+p2+p3 into a new Group g ===
#[sub] `objects group p1 p2 p3` wraps the three paths in a new
#[sub] Group. The verb returns the new Group's iid as text; bind
#[sub] it to `g` so subsequent phases can address it.
#[sub]
#[sub] g child_count == 3 confirms all three children landed in
#[sub] the group; the order of children inside the group is
#[sub] parent-z-order (not selection order), but order isn't
#[sub] asserted here — Phase 5's parent_iid asserts are order-
#[sub] independent.

objects group p1 p2 p3
set g to result

assert objects.g type == "group"
assert objects.g child_count == 3

#[sub] === Phase 5: VERIFY children parented to g ===
#[sub] Each child's parent_iid should now resolve to g (the new
#[sub] Group's iid). This confirms the children actually moved
#[sub] into the group rather than just having the group inserted
#[sub] alongside them — a regression in the verb's tree-mutation
#[sub] could conceivably create the group without re-parenting,
#[sub] which the count and child_count asserts wouldn't catch but
#[sub] this would.

assert objects.p1 parent_iid == g
assert objects.p2 parent_iid == g
assert objects.p3 parent_iid == g

#[sub] === Phase 6: UNGROUP — dissolve g, children back to test_layer ===
#[sub] `objects ungroup g` dissolves the Group, promoting its
#[sub] children to the parent (test_layer) at the Group's original
#[sub] index. After this, each child's parent_iid resolves to
#[sub] test_layer again.

objects ungroup g

assert objects.p1 parent_iid == test_layer
assert objects.p2 parent_iid == test_layer
assert objects.p3 parent_iid == test_layer

#[sub] === Phase 7: NEGATIVE — group single-arg refused ===
#[sub] The verb requires args.size() >= 2 (matching Canvas's
#[sub] "group ≥ 2 selected" convention). Single-arg group is a
#[sub] silent no-op; the verb returns "" and no command is pushed.
#[sub] The assert verifies p1 is still parented to test_layer
#[sub] (it didn't get accidentally wrapped in a 1-child group).

objects group p1

assert objects.p1 parent_iid == test_layer

#[sub] === Phase 8: NEGATIVE — ungroup wrong-type refused ===
#[sub] `objects ungroup p1` attempts to ungroup a Path. The verb
#[sub] checks node->type == Group and refuses if not — p1 stays
#[sub] a Path under test_layer. Same shape as set_path_data's
#[sub] non-Path refusal, just on the structural side.

objects ungroup p1

assert objects.p1 type == "path"

#[sub] === Phase 9: REGROUP — re-wrap to confirm the verb is repeatable ===
#[sub] After Phase 6's ungroup, the children are siblings under
#[sub] test_layer again. Group them again — the new Group g2 gets
#[sub] a FRESH iid (the old g's iid is gone from the live tree —
#[sub] only re-resurrectable via Ctrl+Z, which scripts don't do).
#[sub] This phase confirms the verb is purely repeatable; nothing
#[sub] in the first round left state that prevents a second round.

objects group p1 p2 p3
set g2 to result

assert objects.g2 type == "group"
assert objects.g2 child_count == 3

#[sub] === Phase 10: CROSS-CHECK — find_by_type "group" resolves ===
#[sub] Sanity check that the new group is addressable via the
#[sub] standard tree-walking surface. find_by_type "group" walks
#[sub] depth-first and returns the first hit's iid; with g2 the
#[sub] only group in scope, the first hit IS g2.

objects find_by_type "group"
set found_group to result
assert objects.found_group type == "group"

#[sub] === Phase 11: TEAR DOWN — subtree-delete the group ===
#[sub] `objects delete g2` removes the group AND its children in
#[sub] one shot (DeleteObjectCommand erases the parent's unique_ptr
#[sub] to g2, which owns the whole subtree). Then delete the test
#[sub] layer.

objects delete g2
layers delete test_layer

get objects count
assert objects count == count_before

#[sub] === Final list — registry sanity ===
#[sub] `objects` still present; no transient proxies registered.

list

#[sub] Done. The s242 m2 surface is validated:
#[sub]   - `objects group <iid1> <iid2> ...` accepts 2+ iids, all
#[sub]     must be siblings, returns the new Group's iid as text.
#[sub]     Pushes GroupNodesCommand (s242 m1 iid-migrated structural
#[sub]     command). Cross-parent and single-arg cases refuse
#[sub]     atomically with "" return.
#[sub]   - `objects ungroup <iid>` accepts 1 iid that must resolve
#[sub]     to a Group, dissolves it, returns null. Pushes
#[sub]     UngroupNodeCommand. Non-Group and empty-Group cases
#[sub]     refuse silently.
#[sub]   - Both verbs are now advertised in ObjectsScriptable::verbs().
#[sub]   - The canvas-observable arc's m5 close lands. The `objects`
#[sub]     Tier 3 entry now books. Six scriptables → seven.
#[sub]
#[sub] Pre-stated: 15 pass / 0 fail / 0 error.
#[sub]
#[sub] What's still NOT covered by s242 m2 (backlog):
#[sub]   - Cross-parent refusal (mint a second layer, place objects
#[sub]     across both, try to group across). Smoke-expansion item.
#[sub]   - Group containing a Group (nested grouping). Should work
#[sub]     by construction — a Group is in-scope and can be one of
#[sub]     the targets — but not explicitly exercised here.
#[sub]   - Undo / redo from script. The DSL has no undo verb; canvas-
#[sub]     side manual testing (s242 m1) confirmed both directions.
#[sub]   - Element-level group manipulation (move a child INTO an
#[sub]     existing group via script). Adjacent surface; future
#[sub]     work.
#[sub]   - Gradient / swatch bindings (carry-over from s238-s241
#[sub]     backlog).
#[sub]   - mutate_appearance alignment decision (carry-over).
